<br>
<br>
<DIV class="poemtitle">Outsiders</DIV><br>
<TABLE><TR><TD>
<br />
Summers in Sunol, my brother and I caught alligator lizards,<br />
skin like the touch of a stranger’s hand in a dark movie theater.<br />
Turning over a rock is a lot like blowing the roof off<br />
of a suburban home, and seeing the scream inside; my mother’s mouth<br />
turned down like a nun’s hem, my father sequestered<br />
in his room like a soldier in a bunker.<br />
 <br />
Our collie got ran over by a truck.<br />
My brother told me the truck took the dog to heaven.<br />
After that, whenever I thought of death,<br />
I pictured a lonely truck picking me up in the night,<br />
ferrying me to some flashing red signal in the sky.<br />
<br />
<br>
<a class="byline" href="javascript:goauthor('brink')">by Emily Brink</a></td></tr></table><br><br>
<br>
  <img src="images/brink.jpg"><br>
  <a class="artistline" href="javascript:goauthor('jones');">art by Pat Jones</a><br>
